## How we work

### UX and Engineering collaboration

We use workflow labels, pretty closely following the [product development flow](//handbook/product-development-flow/#workflow-summary), to indicate that an issue needs design work. We add `~workflow::ready` for design when an issue is ready to be taken on by design. Design is responsible for capturing issues that could be taken on in the next milestone, and communicating with the PM and engineering to finalize the list.

When design takes on an issue, the `~workflow::design` label is applied and the [UX DoD](/handbook/product/ux/stage-group-ux-strategy/ci-cd/#ux-definition-of-done-dod) should be added into the description. During the design process, a technical writer is brought into the process to be able to review the UI copy throughout the iterations. If copy was approved, then a comment is left on the issue saying so. Collaboration with development should also be consistent throughout the design process - this especially helps with considering the feasibility of features.

Once design is approved, the `~workflow::ready for development` label is applied. Design and development should collaborate to ensure the issue is properly broken down and planned for development. 

Issues will not get a milestone attached to them until they are considered as a candidate for an upcoming milestone.

### UX Definition of Done (DoD)

We use the [CI/CD UX Definition of Done (DoD)](/handbook/product/ux/stage-group-ux-strategy/ci-cd/#ux-definition-of-done-dod) as a tool for assessing the readiness of an issue and tracking the expected deliverables, objectives, and the approval process. 

### UX Weight

We use the [UX Weight definitions](/handbook/product/ux/product-designer/#ux-weight-definitions) for milestone capacity.

